<DOC><DOCNO> AP880701-0050 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-01-88 0337EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     07-01 0487</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,500</SECOND><HEAD>Political Arm of Nation's Largest Teacher Union Backs Dukakis</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The political action committee of theNational Education Association, the nation's largest teacher'sunion, has given Democratic presidential hopeful Michael Dukakisits backing for his party's nomination.   The decision came Thursday during a closed-door meeting of NEA'spolitical action committee prior to the teacher group's annualconvention scheduled in New Orleans next week.   Dukakis ``believes in and supports a view and a vision ofeducation policy consistent with our efforts to assure every childa quality education,'' said NEA president Mary Hatwood Futrell.   The endorsement, which applies only to the Democraticnomination, won't become official until today, when the NEA boardof directors is scheduled to meet and is almost certainly to concurwith NEA-PAC's choice.   NEA officials said the 1.9 million-member union plans to witholda final presidential endorsement until Sept. 8, after both partieshave held their conventions.   Dukakis picked up his first formal labor endorsement onWednesday from the 59,000-member National Treasury Employees Union,a group that represents mostly federal Internal Revenue Service andCustoms Service workers.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Police Say More Protest Facilities Could Endanger Security</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Atlanta police officials are urging the courtsnot to expand facilities for demonstrators during next month'sDemocratic National Convention.   Police said Thursday it would confound security plans for theevent.   An umbrella dissident group, Alternative '88, is suing the cityof Atlanta in U.S. District Court for additional space for protestsnear The Omni, the site of the July 18-21 convention.   The city has leased two parking lots, covering about two acres,about half a block from The Omni on Marietta Street. Several groupshave applied for parade permits down Marietta.   But Deputy Police Chief Willie Taylor testified the premits weredenied because demonstrators might chose to lie down in MariettaStreet as a form of protest and that would block delegate access tothe convention hall.   Judge Orinda Evans, who is hearing the case without a jury,continued it until today after two days of testimony.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Thousands Register Through New State Program</HEAD><DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The secretary of state's office says allbut about 600,000 of Minnesota's eligible voters are registered.   Officials are crediting state incentive programs designed toincrease participation in elections with the high registrationnumbers.   About 85,000 Minnesotans have returned voter registration formsthat were mailed for the first time this year with their income taxbooklets.   People applying for or renewing driver's licenses also receivevoter registration information, and Secretary of State Joan Growesaid Wednesday that the state has received about 55,000 forms backfrom that effort.   An additional 40,000 to 50,000 forms filled out by driver'slicense applicants are believed to have been sent directly tocounty auditors, Growe said. About 2,000 voter registration formsobtained during visits to other state agencies also have beenreturned, Growe said.</TEXT></DOC>